@baseUrl = https://localhost:60711

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Spam classification test suite — FTTransformerNetwork behind /api/Classification/Predict
#
# Feature schema (8 features, in order):
#   [0] wordCount        total words in the email
#   [1] capsRatio        fraction of characters that are uppercase (0–1)
#   [2] exclamations     count of '!' characters
#   [3] urlCount         number of URLs in the body
#   [4] moneyKeywords    count of money words ("free", "$$$", "winner", "prize", "% off")
#   [5] urgencyKeywords  count of urgency words ("act now", "urgent", "expires", "limited")
#   [6] linkRatio        fraction of words that are part of a link (0–1)
#   [7] avgWordLen       average word length in characters
#
# Training distributions (what the model has actually seen, 50 samples each):
#   SPAM : wordCount 30–80,  capsRatio 0.3–0.7, exclam 3–9, urls 2–5,
#          money 2–4, urgency 2–4, linkRatio 0.2–0.5, avgWordLen 3–5
#   LEGIT: wordCount 50–300, capsRatio 0–0.1,   exclam 0–1, urls 0–1,
#          money 0 (always),  urgency 0,         linkRatio 0–0.05, avgWordLen 5–7.5
#
# Reading the response:
#   rawScore   = P(spam), softmax output in [0,1]; prediction = "spam" iff ≥ 0.5
#   accuracy   = fraction correct, present only when ALL samples carry a "label"
#   timings    = first request per process also pays one-time training (trainMs);
#                every later request is inference-only
#
# Note: moneyKeywords is a perfect separator in the training data (legit is ALWAYS 0,
# spam is ALWAYS ≥ 2) — several tests below deliberately exploit that gap.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


### 1. Smoke test — textbook spam, squarely inside the spam training distribution
# Sample A: classic "YOU ARE A WINNER!!!" lottery scam — short, 62% caps, 7 '!',
#           5 links, money + urgency words everywhere, tiny words.
# Sample B: "FREE pills, ACT NOW" pharma blast — same profile, slightly tamer.
# EXPECTED: 200 OK; both predicted "spam" with rawScore ≳ 0.99 (saturated softmax,
#           train loss < 5e-4 on this exact distribution); accuracy = 1.0.
#           First call of the process: trainMs > 0 reported; afterwards ~0 marginal.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [22,  0.62, 7, 5, 4, 3, 0.45, 3.2], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [35,  0.60, 5, 3, 3, 2, 0.35, 3.8], "label": 1 }
  ]
}


### 2. Smoke test — textbook legit, squarely inside the legit training distribution
# Sample A: 210-word project status update from a colleague — calm prose, no links.
# Sample B: 145-word meeting recap with one shared-doc link and one polite "!".
# EXPECTED: 200 OK; both predicted "not-spam" with rawScore ≲ 0.01; accuracy = 1.0.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [210, 0.03, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.01, 6.8], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [145, 0.07, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0.03, 5.9], "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 3. CHALLENGE — professionally written phishing (spam disguised as legit)
# A real-world "your account will be suspended, verify your billing details" phish:
# 120 words of clean corporate prose (capsRatio 0.06, one '!', avgWordLen 5.4 — all
# LEGIT territory) but 3 URLs, 3 money keywords, 3 urgency keywords (all SPAM
# territory). 4 features vote legit, 3 vote spam — the model never saw this mix.
# EXPECTED (verified): the model is FOOLED — "not-spam" with rawScore ≈ 0.013,
#           accuracy = 0.0. The surface features (wordCount, capsRatio, avgWordLen)
#           dominate the decision and the keyword counts barely register, even
#           though moneyKeywords > 0 never occurs for legit in training. This is a
#           genuine FALSE NEGATIVE and the most important finding in the suite:
#           polished phishing sails straight through this model.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [120, 0.06, 1, 3, 3, 3, 0.06, 5.4], "label": 1 }
  ]
}


### 4. CHALLENGE — legitimate marketing newsletter (false-positive bait)
# An opted-in retailer sale email: "Summer sale — 20% off this weekend". 90 words,
# capsRatio 0.12 (brand name in caps — just ABOVE the legit max of 0.1), 2 '!',
# 2 URLs (shop + unsubscribe — above legit max of 1), 1 money keyword ("% off"),
# 1 urgency keyword ("this weekend only"). Every feature sits in the no-man's-land
# between the two training clusters.
# EXPECTED (verified): correctly "not-spam", rawScore ≈ 0.001, accuracy = 1.0.
#           No false positive — the moneyKeywords = 1 pull toward spam is swamped
#           by the legit-looking length/caps profile. Together with test 3 this
#           shows the model leans heavily toward "not-spam" whenever the prose
#           statistics look normal, regardless of keyword signals.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [90, 0.12, 2, 2, 1, 1, 0.07, 5.2], "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 5. CHALLENGE — short personal note (out-of-distribution legit)
# "Thanks! See you at 3pm." — 6 words, one '!', no links, no spam vocabulary.
# Humans read this as obviously legit, but wordCount 6 is BELOW both training
# ranges (legit starts at 50) and avgWordLen 4.2 falls in the SPAM band (3–5).
# The only strong legit signals are the zeros in money/urgency/urls.
# EXPECTED (verified): correctly "not-spam" with rawScore ≈ 0.0004 — just as
#           confident as the in-distribution legit samples of test 2. The zeros in
#           urls/money/urgency win decisively; the short length and small words do
#           NOT flip it, so the model has not over-weighted message length.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [6, 0.08, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0.0, 4.2], "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 6. CHALLENGE — maximum-ambiguity probe (unlabeled, boundary diagnostics)
# Every feature is set to the midpoint between the two class distributions:
# 65 words (overlap zone), 20% caps, 2 '!', 2 URLs, 1 money, 1 urgency,
# linkRatio 0.12, avgWordLen 4.9. There is no "right answer" by construction.
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK, no "accuracy" field (sample is unlabeled,
#           correct = null). rawScore ≈ 0.004 → "not-spam" — nearly saturated even
#           at the exact midpoint of the two distributions. The decision boundary
#           is razor-thin and sits well on the SPAM side of the midpoint; the model
#           has no calibrated uncertainty (a consequence of training to loss < 5e-4
#           on 100 perfectly separated samples).
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [65, 0.20, 2, 2, 1, 1, 0.12, 4.9] }
  ]
}


### 7. CHALLENGE — extreme extrapolation (numerical-stability test)
# Sample A: cartoonish mega-spam far beyond training: 5000 words, 100% caps,
#           50 '!', 40 URLs, 20 money + 15 urgency keywords, 95% links. After
#           z-score normalization these are huge z-values (e.g. caps ≈ +3.5σ,
#           urls ≈ +25σ) — stress-tests attention/softmax far off the manifold.
# Sample B: extreme legit: a 2000-word essay, zero everything, avgWordLen 9.
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK with finite rawScores — no NaN, no 500 — and both
#           classified correctly at saturation (A ≈ 0.9999 spam, B ≈ 0.0001
#           not-spam), accuracy = 1.0. Attention + softmax stay numerically stable
#           at +25σ inputs.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [5000, 1.0, 50, 40, 20, 15, 0.95, 2.5], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [2000, 0.0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.0, 9.0],      "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 8. CHALLENGE — decision-boundary sweep (monotonicity check, unlabeled)
# Five samples linearly interpolated from a clear-legit anchor (row 1) to a
# clear-spam anchor (row 5) in equal steps — a 1-D walk straight across the
# decision boundary in feature space.
# EXPECTED (verified): rawScore increases MONOTONICALLY down the list —
#           ≈ 0.0002 → 0.0005 → 0.32 → 0.999 → 0.9998 — with the 0.5 crossing
#           between rows 3 and 4. Row 3 (the exact midpoint, money/urgency = 2) is
#           the ONLY point in the whole suite where the model produces a
#           non-saturated score (≈ 0.32): the transition band is extremely narrow
#           but the surface across it is smooth, not lumpy.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [220, 0.03, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.02, 6.5] },
    { "features": [175, 0.16, 2, 1, 1, 1, 0.12, 5.8] },
    { "features": [130, 0.29, 3, 2, 2, 2, 0.21, 5.1] },
    { "features": [85,  0.42, 5, 3, 2, 2, 0.31, 4.3] },
    { "features": [40,  0.55, 6, 4, 3, 3, 0.40, 3.6] }
  ]
}


### 9. Realistic mixed inbox — 12-message batch (batched inference + accuracy)
# Simulates one classification pass over an inbox:
#   rows 1–4   easy spam   (lottery scam, pharma blast, crypto pump, fake invoice)
#   rows 5–8   easy legit  (status update, meeting recap, long report, HR notice)
#   rows 9–10  hard spam   (polished phishing — the test-3 pattern, two variants)
#   rows 11–12 hard legit  (sale newsletter, short personal note — tests 4 & 5)
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK; accuracy = 0.8333 (10/12). The two misses are
#           rows 9–10 — the polished-phishing FALSE NEGATIVES (rawScore ≈ 0.029 and
#           0.003), consistent with test 3. The hard-legit rows 11–12 are handled
#           fine. inferenceMs ≈ single-sample latency (~10 ms), confirming the
#           [12,8] batch runs as ONE tensor through the network rather than 12
#           sequential calls.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [25,  0.65, 8, 5, 4, 4, 0.48, 3.1], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [42,  0.48, 6, 4, 3, 3, 0.38, 3.9], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [55,  0.35, 4, 3, 2, 2, 0.25, 4.4], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [70,  0.40, 5, 2, 3, 4, 0.22, 4.0], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [180, 0.04, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.01, 6.5], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [95,  0.06, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0.04, 5.7], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [280, 0.02, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0.02, 7.2], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [120, 0.09, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0.00, 6.1], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [110, 0.07, 1, 3, 3, 3, 0.08, 5.3], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [140, 0.05, 0, 4, 2, 2, 0.10, 5.6], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [90,  0.12, 2, 2, 1, 1, 0.07, 5.2], "label": 0 },
    { "features": [6,   0.08, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0.00, 4.2], "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 10. Validation — wrong feature count
# Only 3 of the required 8 features supplied.
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request, body names the offending sample index ("Sample 0")
#           and lists all 8 expected feature names. No inference is run.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [22, 0.62, 7], "label": 1 }
  ]
}


### 11. Validation — bad sample buried mid-batch (fail-fast, atomic rejection)
# Sample 0 is valid; sample 1 has 9 features. The whole request must be rejected —
# partial results for a half-valid batch would be worse than an error.
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request naming "Sample 1" specifically; the valid sample 0 is
#           NOT classified.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "features": [22, 0.62, 7, 5, 4, 3, 0.45, 3.2], "label": 1 },
    { "features": [210, 0.03, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0.01, 6.8, 99], "label": 0 }
  ]
}


### 12. Validation — empty samples array
# EXPECTED: 400 Bad Request — "Provide at least one sample to classify."
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": []
}


### 13. Validation — sample with null/missing features
# The "features" property is absent entirely.
# EXPECTED (verified): 400 Bad Request — but from MODEL BINDING, not the controller:
#           an RFC 9110 ValidationProblemDetails body with
#           errors["Samples[0].Features"] = "The Features field is required."
#           (non-nullable record parameter ⇒ [ApiController] rejects before the
#           action runs). Different error shape than tests 10–12.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/Predict
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "samples": [
    { "label": 1 }
  ]
}


# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# PredictText — raw text in, classification out
# SpamFeatureExtractor derives the 8-feature vector from each message
# (URL regex, money/urgency keyword patterns, caps/word statistics) and the
# extracted features are echoed in every prediction so the derivation is
# auditable. Same trained model as Predict.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


### 14. PredictText — real message texts across the difficulty spectrum
# Message 1: classic shouty scam blast. Extracted (verified): wordCount=25,
#            capsRatio=0.43, exclamations=8, urlCount=2, moneyKeywords=6,
#            urgencyKeywords=4, linkRatio=0.08, avgWordLen=4.59 — lands squarely
#            in the spam training distribution.
# Message 2: ordinary 85-word project email. Extracted: capsRatio=0.018, all
#            keyword counts 0 — squarely legit.
# Message 3: 8-word personal note — out-of-distribution short legit (the test-5
#            pattern from the feature-level suite).
# EXPECTED (verified): accuracy = 1.0 —
#            msg1 → spam (rawScore ≈ 0.9997), msg2 → not-spam (≈ 0.0003),
#            msg3 → not-spam (≈ 0.0005; the zero keyword counts win despite the
#            spam-like brevity).
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/PredictText
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "messages": [
    {
      "text": "CONGRATULATIONS WINNER!!! You WON a FREE cash PRIZE! Claim your $$$ at http://bit.ly/claim-now and http://win-big.io NOW! Offer expires TODAY, act now, LIMITED time only! HURRY!!",
      "label": 1
    },
    {
      "text": "Hi team, following up on yesterday's planning meeting. We agreed to move the database migration to next sprint so that the reporting work can finish first. Sarah will update the timeline document and share it before Friday. Please review the updated estimates when you get a chance and add any concerns as comments. The staging environment will be unavailable on Thursday morning while operations applies security patches. Thanks everyone for the productive discussion, and let me know if anything important is missing from the notes.",
      "label": 0
    },
    {
      "text": "Thanks! See you at the meeting at 3pm.",
      "label": 0
    }
  ]
}


### 15. PredictText CHALLENGE — polished phishing email (end-to-end false negative)
# A realistic account-suspension phish written in clean corporate prose: no
# shouting, no exclamation marks, but two phishing links, a money reference and
# a deadline. Extracted (verified): wordCount=66, capsRatio=0.024,
# exclamations=0, urlCount=2, moneyKeywords=1, urgencyKeywords=1,
# linkRatio=0.03, avgWordLen=5.06 — the surface features all read "legit".
# EXPECTED (verified): "not-spam" with rawScore ≈ 0.0007 — a CONFIDENT FALSE
#            NEGATIVE, accuracy = 0.0. This reproduces the feature-level test-3
#            finding end-to-end from raw text: the model keys on prose
#            statistics, and polished phishing is indistinguishable from a
#            normal business email in those statistics.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/PredictText
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "messages": [
    {
      "text": "Dear customer, we detected unusual activity on your account. To avoid suspension, please verify your billing information at https://secure-verify.example.com/account within 24 hours. A refund of 49.99 is pending and will be released once verification is complete. For your security, this link expires today. If you have questions about this charge or your cash back balance, visit https://billing.example.com/help. Thank you for your prompt attention. Account Services Team",
      "label": 1
    }
  ]
}


### 16. PredictText validation — empty messages array
# EXPECTED (verified): 400 Bad Request — "Provide at least one message to classify."
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/PredictText
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "messages": []
}


### 17. PredictText validation — whitespace-only text
# EXPECTED (verified): 400 Bad Request — "Message 0: text must be a non-empty string."
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Classification/PredictText
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "messages": [
    { "text": "   " }
  ]
}
